00:07:32,738 --> 00:07:34,167
So I was called Bosegi.

241
00:07:34,168 --> 00:07:35,667
- Oh, "Bosegi."
- I see.

242
00:07:35,668 --> 00:07:36,707
- "Bosegi."
- "Bosegi."

243
00:07:36,708 --> 00:07:38,737
Oh, I had another nickname that my friends gave me.

244
00:07:38,738 --> 00:07:40,107
- What is it?
- Wench.

245
00:07:40,108 --> 00:07:41,637
- "Wench?"
- Because you looked so pretty?

246
00:07:41,638 --> 00:07:43,347
- As in "girl."
- "Girl?"

247
00:07:43,348 --> 00:07:44,648
- That wasn't the case.
- Because you were handsome.

248
00:07:44,778 --> 00:07:46,878
Right before I started elementary school,

249
00:07:47,248 --> 00:07:48,848
my parents had my hair permed.

250
00:07:49,648 --> 00:07:52,688
Back then, there were hairdressers in the countryside who offered...

251
00:07:52,958 --> 00:07:55,217
- door-to-door perming services.
- That's right.

252
00:07:55,218 --> 00:07:56,487
- They were called Ms. Hair Roller.
- Me too.

253
00:07:56,488 --> 00:07:58,327
So my elders were getting a perm,

254
00:07:58,328 --> 00:08:00,497
and they had my hair permed too.

255
00:08:00,498 --> 00:08:01,627
Oh, you mean, the pinkle perm?

256
00:08:01,628 --> 00:08:02,697
- Yes.
- The pinkle perm?

257
00:08:02,698 --> 00:08:04,027
No, I mean, I had small, tight curls all over my head.

258
00:08:04,028 --> 00:08:05,337
- Small, tight curls.
- I see.

259
00:08:05,338 --> 00:08:07,437
I had to go to school, but I was embarrassed.

260
00:08:07,438 --> 00:08:09,538
So I wore a beanie...

261
00:08:09,808 --> 00:08:11,467
to my entrance ceremony.

262
00:08:11,468 --> 00:08:13,537
I was told to take off my beanie,

263
00:08:13,538 --> 00:08:14,777
but I didn't.

264
00:08:14,778 --> 00:08:17,707
My teacher pulled my beanie, telling me to take it off.

265
00:08:17,708 --> 00:08:18,717
It was like that back in the day.

266
00:08:18,718 --> 00:08:21,018
I just stormed out of the classroom, saying I wouldn't go back to school.

267
00:08:21,518 --> 00:08:22,788
Since then...

268
00:08:23,018 --> 00:08:24,817
My beanie fell off when the teacher pulled it.

269
00:08:24,818 --> 00:08:26,357
My classmates saw my hair and laughed.

270
00:08:26,358 --> 00:08:28,117
- They started calling me a girl.
- "Wench?"

271
00:08:28,118 --> 00:08:29,357
- I see.
- It's because he was so pretty.

272
00:08:29,358 --> 00:08:30,757
- All pretty boys have nicknames...
- Right.

273
00:08:30,758 --> 00:08:32,657
- like "Sissy" and "Wench."
- For little boys...

274
00:08:32,658 --> 00:08:33,827
I, too, had nicknames like those.

275
00:08:33,828 --> 00:08:35,127
- For little boys...
- It was the same for you, right?

276
00:08:35,128 --> 00:08:38,067
- Yes.
- Getting a perm as a little boy...

277
00:08:38,068 --> 00:08:39,837
wasn't very common back then.

278
00:08:39,838 --> 00:08:41,297
- No boys had their hair permed.
- So kids would tease you.

279
00:08:41,298 --> 00:08:43,438
- Right.
- When I was little...

280
00:08:43,638 --> 00:08:44,737
You had your hair permed too?

281
00:08:44,738 --> 00:08:47,177
- When I was little, my mom...
- That doesn't sound like him.

282
00:08:47,178 --> 00:08:50,007
completely caught me off guard when she decided...

283
00:08:50,008 --> 00:08:51,547
to get my hair permed.

284
00:08:51,548 --> 00:08:53,077
And my hair looked so weird.

285
00:08:53,078 --> 00:08:55,177
I was already ugly. On top of my ugly face...

286
00:08:55,178 --> 00:08:56,317
I know what you mean.

287
00:08:56,318 --> 00:08:57,787
With the permed hair,

288
00:08:57,788 --> 00:08:59,718
I looked so weird. And other kids...

289
00:08:59,988 --> 00:09:01,917
I was the only one with permed hair,

290
00:09:01,918 --> 00:09:03,487
- and other kids teased me.
- Right.

291
00:09:03,488 --> 00:09:04,857
"Look at his permed hair."

292
00:09:04,858 --> 00:09:07,597
I had the perm undone the very next day.

293
00:09:07,598 --> 00:09:08,967
- You had it undone?
- I had it undone.

294
00:09:08,968 --> 00:09:11,028
Why didn't you straighten out those frowns too?

295
00:09:14,038 --> 00:09:15,038
Yes!

296
00:09:15,039 --> 00:09:16,507
That's just how funny Soo Geun can be.

297
00:09:16,508 --> 00:09:18,338
(Straighten out your frowns instead of your hair.)

298
00:09:19,578 --> 00:09:20,707
That was good.

299
00:09:20,708 --> 00:09:21,708
(Is Jang Hoon curling his arm so that he can never straighten it?)

300
00:09:21,709 --> 00:09:22,777
- Oh, my goodness.
- That was great.

301
00:09:22,778 --> 00:09:24,807
(The Brother Barber is always open.)

302
00:09:24,808 --> 00:09:26,147
- Nice.
- By the way,

303
00:09:26,148 --> 00:09:27,517
- That was really nice.
- I didn't know...

304
00:09:27,518 --> 00:09:28,687
perms could be undone back then.

305
00:09:28,688 --> 00:09:29,747
- They could do that.
- Exactly.

306
00:09:29,748 --> 00:09:31,987
But they couldn't get the hair perfectly straight.

307
00:09:31,988 --> 00:09:33,887
- Using chemicals?
- It was still a bit curly.

308
00:09:33,888 --> 00:09:36,087
- Using hair straightening solution.
- So I had it cut really short.

309
00:09:36,088 --> 00:09:37,288
I was embarrassed by the curls.

310
00:09:37,658 --> 00:09:39,527
- Ji Won's nickname is...
- Yejiryeok as in "foresight."

311
00:09:39,528 --> 00:09:41,397
- It's hard to guess.
- Exactly, "Yejiryeok."

312
00:09:41,398 --> 00:09:44,327
What does this mean? You wrote, "Quack Doctor."

313
00:09:44,328 --> 00:09:46,637
- My nickname is Quack Doctor.
- Why?

314
00:09:46,638 --> 00:09:48,968
You can call me a health promoter if you mean it in a good way.

315
00:09:49,508 --> 00:09:51,838
I call myself a health promoter.

316
00:09:51,938 --> 00:09:54,008
But other people call me a quack.

317
00:09:54,208 --> 00:09:57,408
- Did something happen?
- What made you promote health?

318
00:09:57,608 --> 00:10:00,448
Back in my late 30s, I wasn't exactly sick,

319
00:10:00,818 --> 00:10:02,947
- but I just felt like...
- Like you were losing your edge.

320
00:10:02,948 --> 00:10:05,087
- Like you were getting weak? Right.
- I was losing my edge.

321
00:10:05,088 --> 00:10:09,228
That's when I started learning about good food for my constitution.

322
00:10:09,558 --> 00:10:12,958
- I went to see some TCM doctors.
- Then, what happened?

323
00:10:13,298 --> 00:10:15,928
Then, something magical happened.

324
00:10:16,368 --> 00:10:17,498
I actually became healthier.

325
00:10:17,598 --> 00:10:21,037
- Really?
- Surprisingly, I felt rejuvenated.

326
00:10:21,038 --> 00:10:22,508
- What did you eat?
- You felt rejuvenated?

327
00:10:22,638 --> 00:10:23,907
You just have to neutralize.

328
00:10:23,908 --> 00:10:24,967
- Sorry?
- You have to neutralize.

329
00:10:24,968 --> 00:10:27,038
- How?
- Using food.

330
00:10:27,638 --> 00:10:30,248
You have to neutralize the foods that don't work for you...

331
00:10:30,478 --> 00:10:32,947
with those that do.

332
00:10:32,948 --> 00:10:35,988
For example, you eat seafood with some beef.

333
00:10:36,248 --> 00:10:38,348
- Yes, eat those together.
- Oh, I see.

334
00:10:38,588 --> 00:10:39,657
- In that case...
- Like clams, for example.

335
00:10:39,658 --> 00:10:43,357
In the play, there's a scene where our partner lifts us up.

336
00:10:43,358 --> 00:10:44,888
And she's thinner than me.

337
00:10:44,988 --> 00:10:46,327
I was so surprised when I heard her weight.

338
00:10:46,328 --> 00:10:47,397
- It seems that way.
- She weighs only 40kg...

339
00:10:47,398 --> 00:10:48,527
It definitely looks that way.

340
00:10:48,528 --> 00:10:50,967
- You see...
- She's good at self-management.

341
00:10:50,968 --> 00:10:52,097
- I'm good at self-management too.
- I wasn't, in my younger years.

342
00:10:52,098 --> 00:10:54,298
Don't talk about weight from now on.

343
00:10:54,998 --> 00:10:56,267
Don't talk about weight.

344
00:10:56,268 --> 00:10:58,107
- Thank you, Shin Young.
- Ha Sun's nickname is...

345
00:10:58,108 --> 00:10:59,677
- Actually, Ha Sun's nicknames...
- What's Ha Sun's nickname?

346
00:10:59,678 --> 00:11:02,678
- are perfect for our purpose.
- Really?

347
00:11:02,748 --> 00:11:03,808
Her nicknames from her childhood are...

348
00:11:03,908 --> 00:11:05,307
- Park Ha Sun's nicknames are...
- Mint Candy?

349
00:11:05,308 --> 00:11:06,547
- Bacchus?
- Mint Candy?

350
00:11:06,548 --> 00:11:07,777
- You're right.
- And Bacchus.

351
00:11:07,778 --> 00:11:09,147
- "Bacchus?"
- And Nakhasan, based on my name.

352
00:11:09,148 --> 00:11:10,488
- "Nakhasan" as in "parachute?"
- Because I have a unique name.

353
00:11:11,218 --> 00:11:12,718
- Park Ha Sun, Nakhasan.
- "Nakhasan."

354
00:11:12,918 --> 00:11:14,587
- They sound similar to each other.
- I was teased so much.

355
00:11:14,588 --> 00:11:15,957
- "Nakhasan?"
- I'm tired of those nicknames.

356
00:11:15,958 --> 00:11:18,158
Next, our transfer students wrote...

357
00:11:18,428 --> 00:11:20,427
- what they had in common.
- What they have in common.

358
00:11:20,428 --> 00:11:22,667
- What we have in common?
- This is why they're here.

359
00:11:22,668 --> 00:11:23,798
Here goes.

360
00:11:24,068 --> 00:11:25,127
The play...

361
00:11:25,128 --> 00:11:26,597
- "Hongdo: A Tragic Love Story."
- That's right.

362
00:11:26,598 --> 00:11:27,637
Is it the name from the song we know...

363
00:11:27,638 --> 00:11:33,508
(Don't cry, Hongdo)

364
00:11:33,838 --> 00:11:34,978
- Like I said - Like I said

365
00:11:35,408 --> 00:11:41,448
(I am here for you)

366
00:11:41,748 --> 00:11:42,817
Is it "Hongdo" from that song?

367
00:11:42,818 --> 00:11:44,187
- Correct.
- That's right.

368
00:11:44,188 --> 00:11:46,887
Exaggerating the pronunciation of the word "cry..."

369
00:11:46,888 --> 00:11:48,287
- Cry.
- heightens the emotional impact.

370
00:11:48,288 --> 00:11:50,557
- That's right.
- There must be a story behind it.

371
00:11:50,558 --> 00:11:52,498
- This is...
- What is it? Is it a play?

372
00:11:52,728 --> 00:11:54,527
It's a play that premiered before the liberation of Korea,

373
00:11:54,528 --> 00:11:56,227
during the Japanese colonial era.

374
00:11:56,228 --> 00:11:58,628
It was the biggest hit before the liberation of Korea.

375
00:11:58,798 --> 00:12:00,097
It was performed at Dongyang Theater,

376
00:12:00,098 --> 00:12:02,667
and it was sensational at the time.

377
00:12:02,668 --> 00:12:04,207
The play was so popular...

378
00:12:04,208 --> 00:12:05,577
that it was made into a movie.

379
00:12:05,578 --> 00:12:06,677
(The movie "Being Lucky Neither at Cards Nor at Love")

380
00:12:06,678 --> 00:12:07,738
(Released in 1939, directed by Lee Myeong Wu)

381
00:12:07,878 --> 00:12:10,277
- The song was featured in it.
- That's right.

382
00:12:10,278 --> 00:12:12,317
- And the song is still famous.
- The song wasn't released first?

383
00:12:12,318 --> 00:12:13,318
("Don't Cry, Hongdo" was the theme song of the movie.)

384
00:12:13,319 --> 00:12:15,347
The play is still just as fun to watch today.

385
00:12:15,348 --> 00:12:17,387
It's been loved for 91 years.

386
00:12:17,388 --> 00:12:18,718
- For 91 years?
- For 91 years?

387
00:12:18,888 --> 00:12:20,057
It's not that it premiered in 1991?

388
00:12:20,058 --> 00:12:22,958
The original play was written by Im Seong Gyu.

389
00:12:23,228 --> 00:12:24,787
We introduced it to you as we came in.

390
00:12:24,788 --> 00:12:26,658
- "Being Lucky Neither at Cards..."
- "Nor at Love."

391
00:12:26,798 --> 00:12:29,797
It's a story about a younger sister and her older brother.

392
00:12:29,798 --> 00:12:31,497
- Yes, that's correct.
- That's right.

393
00:12:31,498 --> 00:12:33,468
- Here's how the story goes.
- The song lyrics tell the story.

394
00:12:33,538 --> 00:12:36,538
It's about two siblings who have nobody but each other.

395
00:12:36,608 --> 00:12:37,807
They're poor.

396
00:12:37,808 --> 00:12:39,877
But the brother wants to study.

397
00:12:39,878 --> 00:12:40,878
He wants to become a detective.

398
00:12:40,879 --> 00:12:42,347
- Hongdo becomes a gisaeng...
- The sister makes a sacrifice.

399
00:12:42,348 --> 00:12:43,408
which is like a Korean geisha.

400
00:12:43,848 --> 00:12:45,678
- She becomes a gisaeng.
- To support her brother?

401
00:12:45,818 --> 00:12:47,978
And then, she meets a man from a rich family...

402
00:12:48,248 --> 00:12:49,387
- and marries him.
- Right.

403
00:12:49,388 --> 00:12:51,817
- Her father-in-law is nice to her.
- That's a relief.

404
00:12:51,818 --> 00:12:54,517
But through a conspiracy, she is unjustly driven out.

405
00:12:54,518 --> 00:12:56,287
So she gets her revenge. That's how the story goes.

406
00:12:56,288 --> 00:12:57,358
(It's about Hongdo's revenge after being driven out.)

407
00:12:57,488 --> 00:12:58,658
Hold on a second.

408
00:12:59,028 --> 00:13:00,097
What's this?

409
00:13:00,098 --> 00:13:02,398
- You keep taking on a new role.
- That was unexpected.

410
00:13:02,468 --> 00:13:04,097
As far as I know...

411
00:13:04,098 --> 00:13:06,538
It must be good to be the director's husband. He got a new role.

412
00:13:06,768 --> 00:13:08,598
- He took on a new role.
- His wife is this show's director.

413
00:13:10,038 --> 00:13:11,367
- My gosh. I envy him.
- I want that kind of role too.

414
00:13:11,368 --> 00:13:12,737
- Introduce me to her.
- I want that kind of role too.

415
00:13:12,738 --> 00:13:15,107
Hee Chul, this is his wife's notebook.

416
00:13:15,108 --> 00:13:16,947
- He must be so happy.
- It's the director's notebook.

417
00:13:16,948 --> 00:13:18,908
It's like "MBC PD Note."

418
00:13:19,178 --> 00:13:20,477
- Exactly.
- That's right.

419
00:13:20,478 --> 00:13:22,048
- It's the director's notebook.
- My gosh.

420
00:13:22,318 --> 00:13:26,317
As far as I know, Ji Won played Hongdo...

421
00:13:26,318 --> 00:13:28,017
- Yes?
- ten years ago. Am I right?

422
00:13:28,018 --> 00:13:29,257
- Yes, she did.
- How did you know that?

423
00:13:29,258 --> 00:13:30,528
- I have my own ways of finding out.
- He's a real fan.

424
00:13:30,858 --> 00:13:32,057
- I'm touched.
- But...

425
00:13:32,058 --> 00:13:34,928
- Doesn't Hongdo age?
- He must know a lot about her.

426
00:13:35,058 --> 00:13:37,227
I got a call a few months ago.

427
00:13:37,228 --> 00:13:38,797
"I don't think you can play Hongdo..."

428
00:13:38,798 --> 00:13:40,697
- Why do they talk like that?
- "because of your age."

429
00:13:40,698 --> 00:13:41,997
- That must've been unexpected.
- I said it was fine with me.

430
00:13:41,998 --> 00:13:43,508
- I see.
- I said I was busy.

431
00:13:43,668 --> 00:13:44,868
- She said she was busy.
- You said you were busy?

432
00:13:45,068 --> 00:13:46,838
- "That's fine. I'm busy anyway."
- It hurt her pride.

433
00:13:47,078 --> 00:13:48,237
- "I'm busy."
- She was actually busy then.

434
00:13:48,238 --> 00:13:49,947
- I was actually busy then.
- She was actually busy.

435
00:13:49,948 --> 00:13:51,608
So I turned it down because I was busy.

436
00:13:51,848 --> 00:13:54,378
After a while, I got another call.

437
00:13:54,648 --> 00:13:57,948
Ten years ago, we performed all over the country.

438
00:13:58,288 --> 00:14:00,757
And I probably left a strong impression.

439
00:14:00,758 --> 00:14:03,528
The owners of the theaters in the regions outside Seoul...

440
00:14:03,858 --> 00:14:07,198
wanted me to play the role again. So I took on the role.

441
00:14:07,598 --> 00:14:09,967
But I can only perform a few times in Seoul.

442
00:14:09,968 --> 00:14:11,368
I'm really sorry to the team,

443
00:14:11,798 --> 00:14:13,367
but I have a scheduling conflict.

444
00:14:13,368 --> 00:14:15,297
- I'll perform in the other regions.
- I see.

445
00:14:15,298 --> 00:14:17,068
She even performed in Abu Dhabi too.

446
00:14:17,208 --> 00:14:18,507
- The team was invited.
- Abu Dhabi?

447
00:14:18,508 --> 00:14:21,538
- Who invited the team?
- Women cried behind their hijabs.

448
00:14:22,608 --> 00:14:27,077
(Hongdo's story was relatable, even beyond the cultural differences.)

449
00:14:27,078 --> 00:14:28,817
- They must've performed in Korean.
- She performed in Abu Dhabi.

450
00:14:28,818 --> 00:14:30,847
- Yes, they performed in Korean.
- Then how did they understand?

451
00:14:30,848 --> 00:14:33,418
- The play provided subtitles.
- I bet the play provided subtitles.

452
00:14:33,718 --> 00:14:35,257
- So they immersed themselves...
- We played at the national theater.

453
00:14:35,258 --> 00:14:36,757
- in the story through the acting?
- At the national theater?

454
00:14:36,758 --> 00:14:38,558
- Yes.
- The play was so well-crafted...

455
00:14:38,828 --> 00:14:40,158
that it could convey the story...

456
00:14:40,598 --> 00:14:43,127
- beyond the language barrier.
- Anyone could follow the story.

457
00:14:43,128 --> 00:14:44,328
- They could relate to it.
- That's right.

458
00:14:44,498 --> 00:14:46,798
You know, Hongdo's in-laws are...

459
00:14:46,968 --> 00:14:48,738
against her marriage.

460
00:14:48,938 --> 00:14:51,167
- They claimed she had an affair...
- She was framed.

461
00:14:51,168 --> 00:14:52,478
- and kicked her out of the house.
- Correct.

462
00:14:52,678 --> 00:14:55,608
- What would you do if you were her?
- If her husband cheated?

463
00:14:55,748 --> 00:14:57,547
- If he's a boyfriend...
- Let's say your boyfriend cheated.

464
00:14:57,548 --> 00:15:00,047
I would just let him go. Why would I keep dating him?

465
00:15:00,048 --> 00:15:01,918
- But if it's my husband...
- Yes, he's your husband.

466
00:15:02,118 --> 00:15:03,188
- I would kill...
- What?

467
00:15:04,648 --> 00:15:07,087
- She said, "I would kill..."
- She would kill him.

468
00:15:07,088 --> 00:15:09,227
- Hongdo kills someone.
- I'm surprised.

469
00:15:09,228 --> 00:15:10,587
- Hongdo kills someone.
- That's right.

470
00:15:10,588 --> 00:15:14,298
What if you fall for someone who is in a relationship?

471
00:15:14,398 --> 00:15:15,867
- Oh, my.
- I would leave the Earth.

472
00:15:15,868 --> 00:15:17,797
- "Leave the Earth."
- It's worth trying.

473
00:15:17,798 --> 00:15:19,138
- But she has a boyfriend...
- She's not married.

474
00:15:19,238 --> 00:15:20,737
- That's true.
- How would you win her over?

475
00:15:20,738 --> 00:15:21,867
I guess you have experience, Bo Seog.

476
00:15:21,868 --> 00:15:23,307
I bet he has a lot of such experiences.

477
00:15:23,308 --> 00:15:24,737
- Back in the day...
- Right? Look how handsome he is.

478
00:15:24,738 --> 00:15:28,238
- Back in the day?
- When I first met my wife,

479
00:15:28,338 --> 00:15:30,048
- Did you take her from another man?
- she was a college freshman.

480
00:15:30,808 --> 00:15:32,278
- At first sight...
- He probably did.

481
00:15:35,948 --> 00:15:38,218
I liked her. I fell for her instantly.

482
00:15:38,688 --> 00:15:39,988
But she had a boyfriend.

483
00:15:41,158 --> 00:15:43,327
So I waited...

484
00:15:43,328 --> 00:15:45,128
because I knew that relationships didn't last long at that age.

485
00:15:45,388 --> 00:15:46,397
I was sure it would end soon.

486
00:15:46,398 --> 00:15:48,198
- You already knew that...
- He was in his senior year.

487
00:15:48,428 --> 00:15:51,068
- You waited for the right time?
- I waited until she broke up.

488
00:15:51,168 --> 00:15:52,667
- So...
- That's unbelievable.

489
00:15:52,668 --> 00:15:55,168
- He didn't go to the same school.
- Okay.

490
00:15:55,368 --> 00:15:57,138
- Her boyfriend, I mean.
- The guy she was seeing?

491
00:15:57,308 --> 00:15:59,408
He always came to our school to see her.

492
00:15:59,908 --> 00:16:03,647
So I thought maybe I should take care of him...

493
00:16:03,648 --> 00:16:06,548
- outside of school. I pondered.
- "Taking care of him?"

494
00:16:07,148 --> 00:16:09,048
- "Taking care of him?"
- But fortunately, they broke up.

495
00:16:09,348 --> 00:16:11,788
So I thought it was the right time to ask her out.

496
00:16:12,348 --> 00:16:14,017
But she started dating...

497
00:16:14,018 --> 00:16:15,658
- one of her classmates.
- Already?

498
00:16:15,888 --> 00:16:18,487
- One of her classmates?
- She got a new boyfriend?

499
00:16:18,488 --> 00:16:20,727
- She was a popular girl.
- She must've been really popular.

500
00:16:20,728 --> 00:16:22,098
But he can't just keep waiting.

501
00:16:22,158 --> 00:16:23,667
But in this case,

502
00:16:23,668 --> 00:16:26,467
- I fell for her before he did.
- That's true.

503
00:16:26,468 --> 00:16:28,968
So I felt I had the right to win her heart.

504
00:16:29,468 --> 00:16:32,238
- You mustered up the courage.
- I started trying...

505
00:16:32,408 --> 00:16:33,837
to keep her by my side.

506
00:16:33,838 --> 00:16:36,848
I gave her tasks that made it necessary for her to be with me.

507
00:16:37,408 --> 00:16:38,507
- And...
- Oh, my.

508
00:16:38,508 --> 00:16:40,677
- There's a lot of group work.
- He was really handsome back then.

509
00:16:40,678 --> 00:16:42,048
- Indeed.
- That's not all.

510
00:16:42,748 --> 00:16:44,518
I even joined the freshmen on their group trip.

511
00:16:44,918 --> 00:16:46,057
- I joined them.
- Oh, my goodness.

512
00:16:46,058 --> 00:16:48,558
- I saw them sitting together.
- He even joined them on the trip?

513
00:16:48,918 --> 00:16:51,557
- I was watching them from behind.
- How scary, just like Jo Pil Yeon.

514
00:16:51,558 --> 00:16:52,797
- The two of them...
- Jo Pil Yeon?

515
00:16:52,798 --> 00:16:54,828
- "Lee Gang Mo!"
- "Lee Gang Mo."

516
00:16:55,458 --> 00:16:57,167
I saw them being all lovey-dovey.

517
00:16:57,168 --> 00:16:58,767
- But I held back my jealousy.
- Oh, boy.

518
00:16:58,768 --> 00:17:00,768
I gathered everyone when we arrived at the destination.

519
00:17:01,038 --> 00:17:04,307
And I said the guys and the girls should be separated...

520
00:17:04,308 --> 00:17:05,738
after 9pm.

521
00:17:06,708 --> 00:17:07,777
(He's simply impressed.)

522
00:17:07,778 --> 00:17:08,937
That's unbelievable.

523
00:17:08,938 --> 00:17:10,347
- A man in love goes to that length.
- That's obsession.

524
00:17:10,348 --> 00:17:11,707
They must've hated...

525
00:17:11,708 --> 00:17:14,147
- that their senior joined them.
- Right.

526
00:17:14,148 --> 00:17:15,747
- Of course.
- On top of that,

527
00:17:15,748 --> 00:17:17,347
I separated the guys and the girls.

528
00:17:17,348 --> 00:17:18,617
I didn't let them see each other.

529
00:17:18,618 --> 00:17:19,758
- The worst senior.
- Right.

530
00:17:20,018 --> 00:17:21,057
- I was the worst.
- Indeed.

531
00:17:21,058 --> 00:17:23,758
- But I didn't care.
- It was for love.

532
00:17:23,858 --> 00:17:26,357
- I was trying to win her heart.
- You were already in love with her.

533
00:17:26,358 --> 00:17:28,057
- Were you back from...
- That's amazing.

534
00:17:28,058 --> 00:17:29,797
your military service at that time?

535
00:17:29,798 --> 00:17:31,567
- Did you serve in the military...
- No, I hadn't served yet.

536
00:17:31,568 --> 00:17:32,768
- You hadn't served yet at the time?
- That's right.

537
00:17:33,238 --> 00:17:36,838
- Lucky for me, her boyfriend...
- Yes?

538
00:17:36,968 --> 00:17:38,207
- Did he enlist in the military?
- liked me.

539
00:17:38,208 --> 00:17:39,537
- What?
- You mean, the guy?

540
00:17:39,538 --> 00:17:41,977
- Her boyfriend liked you?
- Yes, he was fond of me.

541
00:17:41,978 --> 00:17:44,347
- You mean, as a friend?
- It's still weird.

542
00:17:44,348 --> 00:17:46,217
He must've respected Bo Seog as his senior.

543
00:17:46,218 --> 00:17:49,247
I had to put in some effort to separate him from her.

544
00:17:49,248 --> 00:17:51,347
- Of course.
- I worked part-time jobs...

545
00:17:51,348 --> 00:17:52,687
and bought him drinks so many times.

546
00:17:52,688 --> 00:17:55,858
- My goodness.
- I subtly brought her up.

547
00:17:55,988 --> 00:17:58,257
"You know, about her..."

548
00:17:58,258 --> 00:17:59,897
Eventually, he noticed my feelings.

549
00:17:59,898 --> 00:18:00,997
- Right.
- Yes.

550
00:18:00,998 --> 00:18:03,068
- Did he give up on her?
- Yes, he did.

551
00:18:03,368 --> 00:18:05,767
- That's romantic.
- Right. Usually...

552
00:18:05,768 --> 00:18:07,237
- That's romantic.
- What happened...

553
00:18:07,238 --> 00:18:08,667
when you asked her out?

554
00:18:08,668 --> 00:18:10,007
We're married now.

555
00:18:10,008 --> 00:18:12,137
- Did she say yes right away?
- I asked her out right away.

556
00:18:12,138 --> 00:18:14,537
- I mean, did she say yes?
- Did she say yes right away...

557
00:18:14,538 --> 00:18:16,047
- when you asked her out?
- Right away?

558
00:18:16,048 --> 00:18:17,148
To make a long story short...

559
00:18:17,308 --> 00:18:20,518
It took me eight months to ask her out.

560
00:18:21,318 --> 00:18:23,947
I visited all the places to go with her on our date in advance.

561
00:18:23,948 --> 00:18:25,957
- My goodness. He's so persistent.
- That's so sweet.

562
00:18:25,958 --> 00:18:27,688
- So we went there...
- He's a planning type of person.

563
00:18:27,958 --> 00:18:29,218
We went to Cheongpyeong.

564
00:18:29,488 --> 00:18:31,757
There was this place about a 40-minute walk away...

565
00:18:31,758 --> 00:18:33,298
from the train station.

566
00:18:33,898 --> 00:18:35,197
I had reserved a room in advance.

567
00:18:35,198 --> 00:18:38,968
- It was around the end of October.
- He booked a room in Cheongpyeong?

568
00:18:39,128 --> 00:18:40,368
It was a restaurant.

569
00:18:40,538 --> 00:18:42,838
Don't let your imagination run wild. It wasn't a hotel.

570
00:18:43,268 --> 00:18:45,468
- It was a restaurant.
- We didn't imagine anything.

571
00:18:45,538 --> 00:18:47,108
- I wasn't thinking about anything.
- I...

572
00:18:47,278 --> 00:18:51,007
Hee Chul, you looked like you were imagining that kind of thing.

573
00:18:51,008 --> 00:18:53,718
- You're probably right. He would...
- "Lee Gang Mo."

574
00:18:53,948 --> 00:18:55,448
I had made a reservation at this restaurant.

575
00:18:55,948 --> 00:18:57,888
When we were almost there, she didn't seem tired.

576
00:18:58,688 --> 00:19:01,058
So I walked past the place, as if I didn't know it was there.

577
00:19:01,188 --> 00:19:04,227
We walked for another 20 minutes, and she finally got tired.

578
00:19:04,228 --> 00:19:05,257
Why did she have to be tired?

579
00:19:05,258 --> 00:19:07,157
So that she wanted to rest and eat something.

580
00:19:07,158 --> 00:19:08,598
- I needed her to be cold and tired.
- Yes?

581
00:19:08,828 --> 00:19:10,898
Because when you drink soju with some food in that state,

582
00:19:11,228 --> 00:19:12,968
- it'll help you relax.
- Do you pass out?

583
00:19:13,668 --> 00:19:15,467
- Goodness.
- For real.

584
00:19:15,468 --> 00:19:17,807
- What a plan.
- He's Jo Pil Yeon himself.

585
00:19:17,808 --> 00:19:19,637
- Jo Pil Yeon.
- Jo Pil Yeon himself.

586
00:19:19,638 --> 00:19:21,207
- He's Jo Pil Yeon himself.
- Jo Pil Yeon.

587
00:19:21,208 --> 00:19:23,007
- It went beyond my imagination.
- Same here.

588
00:19:23,008 --> 00:19:24,478
("You can win love by being meticulous." By Jung Bo Seog)

589
00:19:24,578 --> 00:19:27,618
- That's the definition of effort.
- It helps you relax...

590
00:19:28,048 --> 00:19:29,517
- and open your heart.
- Of course.

591
00:19:29,518 --> 00:19:30,988
That's when you confess your feelings.

592
00:19:31,318 --> 00:19:32,987
- So I confessed to her.
- Right.

593
00:19:32,988 --> 00:19:35,058
But the thing was, she didn't give me an answer.

594
00:19:35,118 --> 00:19:37,528
Even though I put in all that effort.

595
00:19:37,728 --> 00:19:39,557
- Incredible.
- Without saying a word,

596
00:19:39,558 --> 00:19:42,968
we got a taxi and took a train back to Seoul.

597
00:19:43,268 --> 00:19:45,898
I asked her one more time before getting off the train.

598
00:19:45,998 --> 00:19:47,468
But again, she didn't give me an answer.

599
00:19:47,638 --> 00:19:49,808
- She must've been scared.
- Here's why.

600
00:19:49,968 --> 00:19:52,708
It's hard to meet up once you graduate...

601
00:19:52,838 --> 00:19:54,277
- from college.
- True.

602
00:19:54,278 --> 00:19:57,007
- No phones existed back then.
- Here's the question I asked her.

603
00:19:57,008 --> 00:19:59,617
I asked her to marry me, not to date me.

604
00:19:59,618 --> 00:20:01,817
- What?
- Of course, she wouldn't answer.

605
00:20:01,818 --> 00:20:03,917
I had given her the hint for eight months,

606
00:20:03,918 --> 00:20:06,587
so she had an idea I had feelings for her.

607
00:20:06,588 --> 00:20:07,888
- And she came out on the date.
- My gosh.

608
00:20:08,018 --> 00:20:11,027
I thought she had feelings for me, so I asked her to marry me.

609
00:20:11,028 --> 00:20:12,057
What a real man.

610
00:20:12,058 --> 00:20:13,998
- I hope to fall in such love.
- So cool.

611
00:20:14,158 --> 00:20:15,457
She didn't give me an answer...

612
00:20:15,458 --> 00:20:17,867
when I asked for the last time before getting off the train.

613
00:20:17,868 --> 00:20:19,197
Your wife was too young.

614
00:20:19,198 --> 00:20:20,967
- Exactly.
- True, she was young.

615
00:20:20,968 --> 00:20:22,737
We didn't speak a word...

616
00:20:22,738 --> 00:20:25,567
until I got a taxi and dropped her off.

617
00:20:25,568 --> 00:20:27,208
Right before we reached her house,

618
00:20:28,308 --> 00:20:30,508
I said, "I'm giving up..."

619
00:20:30,778 --> 00:20:32,918
"if you don't give me an answer before getting out of this taxi."

620
00:20:33,648 --> 00:20:35,217
"I will be too busy..."

621
00:20:35,218 --> 00:20:37,647
"and won't have time to put in the effort for you..."

622
00:20:37,648 --> 00:20:39,118
"once I graduate."

623
00:20:39,318 --> 00:20:41,588
"That's why I'm being pushy right now."

624
00:20:41,858 --> 00:20:43,758
She gave me the okay as she got out of the taxi.

625
00:20:44,658 --> 00:20:47,957
Just like that, I went to meet her parents.

626
00:20:47,958 --> 00:20:49,598
- Really?
- Yes.

627
00:20:49,698 --> 00:20:50,727
At 11pm.

628
00:20:50,728 --> 00:20:52,737
- That was short and sweet.
- How is that possible?

629
00:20:52,738 --> 00:20:54,338
- This is interesting.
- Your wife...

630
00:20:54,368 --> 00:20:55,437
was a college freshman, right?

631
00:20:55,438 --> 00:20:57,207
- Yes.
- How is that possible?

632
00:20:57,208 --> 00:20:59,037
- The wedding...
- It was because of his looks.

633
00:20:59,038 --> 00:21:00,637
- Of course.
- Without such a face,

634
00:21:00,638 --> 00:21:02,177
- the parents would've said no.
- During his prime,

635
00:21:02,178 --> 00:21:03,207
- he was like a Hong Kong actor.
- "Hongdo: A Tragic Love Story..."

636
00:21:03,208 --> 00:21:04,247
is good too, but his story...

637
00:21:04,248 --> 00:21:05,707
could be made into a play.

638
00:21:05,708 --> 00:21:06,747
Totally.

639
00:21:06,748 --> 00:21:08,647
- Did her parents approve?
- Yes.

640
00:21:08,648 --> 00:21:10,248
Maybe they were half asleep. It was 11pm.

641
00:21:10,548 --> 00:21:12,347
- "Okay, go ahead."
- Her parents approved,

642
00:21:12,348 --> 00:21:14,457
thinking it was a joke,

643
00:21:14,458 --> 00:21:16,587
but it ended up not being a joke.

644
00:21:16,588 --> 00:21:18,487
- Until they approved...
- When...

645
00:21:18,488 --> 00:21:19,757
When did you get married?

646
00:21:19,758 --> 00:21:21,457
I waited until my wife graduated from college.

647
00:21:21,458 --> 00:21:22,657
So you waited for her.

648
00:21:22,658 --> 00:21:24,467
- How cool.
- Amazing.

649
00:21:24,468 --> 00:21:26,167
- Waiting for her...
- That's youth.

650
00:21:26,168 --> 00:21:27,537
- It wasn't short.
- Don't talk about...

651
00:21:27,538 --> 00:21:28,897
"Hongdo: A Tragic Love Story" today.

652
00:21:28,898 --> 00:21:30,037
- This is way more interesting.
- True.

653
00:21:30,038 --> 00:21:31,867
- So...
- It's like a piece of a play.

654
00:21:31,868 --> 00:21:33,778
- That's why...
- My story isn't even close.

655
00:21:34,078 --> 00:21:35,107
Watch "Hongdo: A Tragic Love Story..."

656
00:21:35,108 --> 00:21:37,077
No, I don't have to. Your story is way more interesting.

657
00:21:37,078 --> 00:21:39,547
Hongdo's husband asks to marry right away.

658
00:21:39,548 --> 00:21:41,578
Correct. Even Hongdo...

659
00:21:42,788 --> 00:21:44,217
- As soon as he meets her...
- Yes.

660
00:21:44,218 --> 00:21:45,417
- She gets asked to marry.
- Yes.

661
00:21:45,418 --> 00:21:46,517
Even though Hongdo is a gisaeng.

662
00:21:46,518 --> 00:21:48,387
Aside from Jo Pil Yeon,

663
00:21:48,388 --> 00:21:49,857
- Bo Seog gives off...
- True.

664
00:21:49,858 --> 00:21:51,127
that warm-hearted vibe.

665
00:21:51,128 --> 00:21:52,428
- Right.
- He does.

666
00:21:52,628 --> 00:21:54,297
But you were very persistent...

667
00:21:54,298 --> 00:21:55,997
- Really.
- back in college.

668
00:21:55,998 --> 00:21:57,798
- Exactly.
- You were persistent.

669
00:21:57,928 --> 00:21:59,327
- The moment I saw her, - Yes?

670
00:21:59,328 --> 00:22:00,868
I thought, "It can't be anyone but her."

671
00:22:01,738 --> 00:22:03,937
- To think you feel that.
- I can totally relate.

672
00:22:03,938 --> 00:22:05,007
Awesome.

673
00:22:05,008 --> 00:22:07,737
Next is "incidents and accidents."

674
00:22:07,738 --> 00:22:08,907
- Incidents and accidents?
- It's under...

675
00:22:08,908 --> 00:22:10,077
what they have in common.

676
00:22:10,078 --> 00:22:12,177
- Ji Won wrote...
- Really.

677
00:22:12,178 --> 00:22:14,178
- "Nosebleed. It hurts."
- "Nosebleed. It hurts?"

678
00:22:14,278 --> 00:22:16,448
- "Nosebleed. It hurts?"
- Right, nosebleed.

679
00:22:16,618 --> 00:22:19,347
Back in "Law of the Jungle," I went to Mongolia.

680
00:22:19,348 --> 00:22:20,557
It was in Mongolia.

681
00:22:20,558 --> 00:22:22,457
Mongolia was a desert.

682
00:22:22,458 --> 00:22:24,027
- Gosh.
- Beautiful, wasn't it?

683
00:22:24,028 --> 00:22:25,527
- It was truly beautiful.
- Of course.

684
00:22:25,528 --> 00:22:27,358
The desert kept changing.

685
00:22:27,458 --> 00:22:30,167
When I woke up in the morning, the surroundings had changed.

686
00:22:30,168 --> 00:22:33,097
One side had turned into a mountain.

687
00:22:33,098 --> 00:22:34,737
- Suddenly?
- Because of the sandstorm?

688
00:22:34,738 --> 00:22:36,468
Yes, it changed.

689
00:22:36,608 --> 00:22:39,138
I thought, "How magical."

690
00:22:39,238 --> 00:22:42,437
"Maybe there's a mirage on top of there."

691
00:22:42,438 --> 00:22:44,478
When I asked the members to join me,

692
00:22:45,208 --> 00:22:46,547
they were too tired...

693
00:22:46,548 --> 00:22:47,848
- as it was morning.
- Right.

694
00:22:47,918 --> 00:22:49,417
The production team was too.

695
00:22:49,418 --> 00:22:51,347
I decided to go alone and did so.

696
00:22:51,348 --> 00:22:54,857
- Alone?
- A cameraman went up with me.

697
00:22:54,858 --> 00:22:56,857
There's always one with a great sense of responsibility.

698
00:22:56,858 --> 00:22:59,187
It was out of friendship. We went up together,

699
00:22:59,188 --> 00:23:01,528
but it was higher than expected,

700
00:23:02,058 --> 00:23:03,527
and our feet kept sinking into the sand.

701
00:23:03,528 --> 00:23:04,627
Yes, since it's sand.

702
00:23:04,628 --> 00:23:06,067
- That sounds dangerous.
- It must've been tough.

703
00:23:06,068 --> 00:23:08,067
- It made it much more difficult.
- Right.

704
00:23:08,068 --> 00:23:10,367
The cameraman stopped midway.

705
00:23:10,368 --> 00:23:12,168
When I turned around,

706
00:23:12,508 --> 00:23:14,008
he was having a nosebleed.

707
00:23:14,438 --> 00:23:16,447
- The cameraman?
- The cameraman had a nosebleed.

708
00:23:16,448 --> 00:23:17,477
It wasn't you?

709
00:23:17,478 --> 00:23:19,207
- No, it was him.
- From the fatigue.

710
00:23:19,208 --> 00:23:22,377
Rumor has it that the cameraman is here with us right now.

711
00:23:22,378 --> 00:23:23,487
- Really?
- Here?

712
00:23:23,488 --> 00:23:25,147
- Is he here?
- Where? Who is it?

713
00:23:25,148 --> 00:23:26,987
- For real?
- The mirage cameraman.

714
00:23:26,988 --> 00:23:29,758
(Looking desperately to find the cameraman)

715
00:23:30,058 --> 00:23:31,887
- Please raise your hand.
- Can you raise your hand?

716
00:23:31,888 --> 00:23:32,957
Is he here with us? Where?

717
00:23:32,958 --> 00:23:34,057
- There he is.
- Really?

718
00:23:34,058 --> 00:23:35,427
- Where?
- Over there.

719
00:23:35,428 --> 00:23:37,428
(Is he the cameraman who had a nosebleed 10 years ago?)

720
00:23:37,528 --> 00:23:38,797
- Where?
- Over there.

721
00:23:38,798 --> 00:23:40,298
- He's over there.
- Seriously?

722
00:23:41,798 --> 00:23:42,937
(Ji Won rushes over to him.)

723
00:23:42,938 --> 00:23:44,437
- Really?
- The nosebleed cameraman.

724
00:23:44,438 --> 00:23:45,468
My gosh.

725
00:23:45,738 --> 00:23:46,777
Did he really have a nosebleed?

726
00:23:46,778 --> 00:23:49,677
- He rarely has nosebleeds.
- Seriously?

727
00:23:49,678 --> 00:23:51,077
- He looks tough.
- He's been with us...

728
00:23:51,078 --> 00:23:52,708
- for ten years.
- Oh, my.

729
00:23:52,748 --> 00:23:54,778
Why'd you get a nosebleed in a different show?

730
00:23:55,918 --> 00:23:57,748
- We went to Micronesia, - Yes?

731
00:23:57,848 --> 00:23:59,957
the Amazon, and Mongolia together.

732
00:23:59,958 --> 00:24:01,217
- Only tough places.
- Those are tough places.

733
00:24:01,218 --> 00:24:02,927
- The cameraman...
- He had it rough.

734
00:24:02,928 --> 00:24:05,557
So when you went up the sand hill, the cameraman had a nosebleed.

735
00:24:05,558 --> 00:24:08,257
Did you wait for him until his bleeding stopped and all?

736
00:24:08,258 --> 00:24:09,698
No, I kept going.

737
00:24:11,068 --> 00:24:13,197
- Who cares if the cameraman faints?
- No, listen.

738
00:24:13,198 --> 00:24:15,897
It was our third trip together, and we had many team dinners before.

739
00:24:15,898 --> 00:24:18,007
It was a true reality show. You just kept going.

740
00:24:18,008 --> 00:24:20,077
- Yes, I knew he was healthy.
- "Just stop..."

741
00:24:20,078 --> 00:24:21,808
"the bleeding with the sand."

742
00:24:22,238 --> 00:24:23,408
I knew he was healthy.

743
00:24:23,848 --> 00:24:26,917
Thanks to "Law of the Jungle," I learned how to do...

744
00:24:26,918 --> 00:24:28,547
- freediving.
- I see.

745
00:24:28,548 --> 00:24:31,248
I was told freediving was a must.

746
00:24:31,888 --> 00:24:34,117
It's true that I dived quite deep into the ocean.

747
00:24:34,118 --> 00:24:36,427
The cameraman back then followed me down,

748
00:24:36,428 --> 00:24:37,688
- but then got a nosebleed.
- A nosebleed.

749
00:24:37,888 --> 00:24:38,957
Another nosebleed?

750
00:24:38,958 --> 00:24:40,697
It's the pressure from going too deep.

751
00:24:40,698 --> 00:24:42,727
And Ji Won was swimming away.

752
00:24:42,728 --> 00:24:44,967
He was trying to catch Ji Won swimming.

753
00:24:44,968 --> 00:24:46,937
- But...
- Everyone started...

754
00:24:46,938 --> 00:24:48,937
hating whatever I did since then.

755
00:24:48,938 --> 00:24:50,707
So it wasn't you who had nosebleeds,

756
00:24:50,708 --> 00:24:52,067
- but other people.
- Nosebleeds.

757
00:24:52,068 --> 00:24:53,107
- But...
- Join Ji Won,

758
00:24:53,108 --> 00:24:54,137
and you get a nosebleed.

759
00:24:54,138 --> 00:24:55,177
It was still fun.

760
00:24:55,178 --> 00:24:57,547
When it comes to Ji Won, she's good at dancing...

761
00:24:57,548 --> 00:24:59,648
- Correct.
- and French.

762
00:24:59,718 --> 00:25:01,617
But I didn't know she could even speak Italian.

763
00:25:01,618 --> 00:25:03,847
- Italian?
- Did you recite the poem?

764
00:25:03,848 --> 00:25:04,918
Buongiorno.

765
00:25:05,488 --> 00:25:06,717
Shall I do it with my mouth covered?

766
00:25:06,718 --> 00:25:08,058
- Why?
- I get shy.

767
00:25:08,488 --> 00:25:09,857
- How come?
- Do you look weird...

768
00:25:09,858 --> 00:25:11,058
when you speak Italian?

769
00:25:11,958 --> 00:25:13,897
- To even have to cover your mouth.
- Buongiorno.

770
00:25:13,898 --> 00:25:15,258
- Buongiorno.
- Here I go.

771
00:25:15,928 --> 00:25:17,727
(When everything around me turned pale, )

772
00:25:17,728 --> 00:25:19,737
(I noticed the fallen leaves scattered across the ground.)

773
00:25:19,738 --> 00:25:21,367
(In that moment, a thought arose within me.)

774
00:25:21,368 --> 00:25:23,867
(How futile it is to bloom in one’s youth.)

775
00:25:23,868 --> 00:25:25,637
- What does it mean?
- How is she so good at it?

776
00:25:25,638 --> 00:25:28,708
You sounded like an Italian flight attendant.

777
00:25:29,238 --> 00:25:32,777
(Like a calm flight attendant speaking on an interphone)

778
00:25:32,778 --> 00:25:35,147
- How can you memorize until now?
- It sounded like an old lady...

779
00:25:35,148 --> 00:25:37,017
- What does it mean?
- complaining while playing hwatu.

780
00:25:37,018 --> 00:25:39,957
"Good grief, my cards are awful."

781
00:25:39,958 --> 00:25:41,817
"Really, how annoying."

782
00:25:41,818 --> 00:25:43,157
(A pro gambler from Italy?)

783
00:25:43,158 --> 00:25:45,158
"That one's a no-go."

784
00:25:45,328 --> 00:25:47,458
(Syncing between an old lady and a flight attendant)

785
00:25:47,498 --> 00:25:49,398
- The tones are similar.
- Exactly.

786
00:25:49,658 --> 00:25:51,828
- "Good grief."
- After getting the cards...

787
00:25:52,198 --> 00:25:55,667
"To think she'd give me cards as terrible as her life."

788
00:25:55,668 --> 00:25:57,437
- "As terrible as her life."
- "Gosh, how annoying."

789
00:25:57,438 --> 00:25:58,737
- "This is the worst."
- In Italian...

790
00:25:58,738 --> 00:26:01,038
- Something like that in Italian.
- What did it mean?

791
00:26:01,478 --> 00:26:04,007
By the way, what was that about?

792
00:26:04,008 --> 00:26:05,807
It's a poem...

793
00:26:05,808 --> 00:26:09,178
written by Lorenzo de' Medici, who helped the Renaissance flourish.

794
00:26:09,618 --> 00:26:12,588
He saw flower petals on the cold ground.

795
00:26:12,718 --> 00:26:15,257
After seeing that, he realized...

796
00:26:15,258 --> 00:26:18,227
the arrogance in his youth was futile.

797
00:26:18,228 --> 00:26:19,527
Something along those lines.

798
00:26:19,528 --> 00:26:21,428
Italian suits her, and she's even good at it.

799
00:26:21,458 --> 00:26:23,227
- How artsy.
- It's pure art.

800
00:26:23,228 --> 00:26:25,498
Next, Bo Seog wrote,

801
00:26:25,828 --> 00:26:27,867
- "Injuries and shotgun."
- What?

802
00:26:27,868 --> 00:26:30,037
- "Injuries and shotgun?"
- "Injuries?"

803
00:26:30,038 --> 00:26:31,607
- Shotgun marriage?
- A shotgun marriage?

804
00:26:31,608 --> 00:26:32,637
Really?

805
00:26:32,638 --> 00:26:35,077
As for injuries, I used to play baseball.

806
00:26:35,078 --> 00:26:36,977
- Yes, I remember.
- Me too.

807
00:26:36,978 --> 00:26:38,947
It wasn't a hobby. He was a former player.

808
00:26:38,948 --> 00:26:40,617
- Was he a player?
- Yes, a player.

809
00:26:40,618 --> 00:26:41,877
- You were a baseball player?
- I actually don't like...

810
00:26:41,878 --> 00:26:43,148
talking about it.

811
00:26:43,348 --> 00:26:46,318
If I had been good at baseball, I would've gone big as a pro player.

812
00:26:46,588 --> 00:26:48,717
Here's the story.

813
00:26:48,718 --> 00:26:51,188
The baseball club in my high school...

814
00:26:51,628 --> 00:26:53,057
disbanded,

815
00:26:53,058 --> 00:26:55,397
so I had to transfer schools.

816
00:26:55,398 --> 00:26:56,767
- So high school baseball.
- I had to transfer schools.

817
00:26:56,768 --> 00:27:00,068
- My friends were already on a roll, - They were improving.

818
00:27:00,138 --> 00:27:01,637
but I was nowhere near them.

819
00:27:01,638 --> 00:27:03,867
Motivated, I was determined to work harder...

820
00:27:03,868 --> 00:27:06,808
and practiced about 12 hours a day.

821
00:27:07,978 --> 00:27:10,748
But as those exercises...

822
00:27:10,908 --> 00:27:12,807
were out of my greed...

823
00:27:12,808 --> 00:27:14,678
and nothing structured or proper,

824
00:27:14,748 --> 00:27:16,147
- I sustained an injury...
- Oh, dear.

825
00:27:16,148 --> 00:27:18,688
- and got a hunchback.
- My gosh.

826
00:27:18,918 --> 00:27:20,287
My back started breaking down.

827
00:27:20,288 --> 00:27:21,317
From overworking, right?

828
00:27:21,318 --> 00:27:23,658
In the end, I had to quit baseball.

829
00:27:23,788 --> 00:27:25,457
With that, I became an actor,

830
00:27:25,458 --> 00:27:27,127
but I think it was for the better.

831
00:27:27,128 --> 00:27:30,167
I've watched Bo Seog's dramas since I was little...

832
00:27:30,168 --> 00:27:31,868
and loved them. But really,

833
00:27:32,428 --> 00:27:34,537
I also think it was for the better.

834
00:27:34,538 --> 00:27:36,767
- Same here.
- Why?

835
00:27:36,768 --> 00:27:38,867
Bo Seog became an actor...

836
00:27:38,868 --> 00:27:40,677
- due to that injury.
- Of course.

837
00:27:40,678 --> 00:27:42,037
Because of that, we're able to watch...

838
00:27:42,038 --> 00:27:43,407
- his great acting.
- Correct.

839
00:27:43,408 --> 00:27:45,477
- It would've been such a waste.
- Totally.

840
00:27:45,478 --> 00:27:47,047
During his prime, he was like a Hong Kong actor.

841
00:27:47,048 --> 00:27:48,077
Right.

842
00:27:48,078 --> 00:27:50,418
I also think it was for the better.

843
00:27:50,548 --> 00:27:51,917
As for shotgun...

844
00:27:51,918 --> 00:27:53,518
- What's that about?
- Isn't it a shotgun wedding?

845
00:27:53,758 --> 00:27:55,357
Correct. Let me explain.

846
00:27:55,358 --> 00:27:57,288
As I have sad memories about baseball,

847
00:27:57,358 --> 00:27:59,827
I turned down invitations to local baseball clubs.

848
00:27:59,828 --> 00:28:01,857
But there was a club...

849
00:28:01,858 --> 00:28:03,768
with juniors I adored.

850
00:28:04,168 --> 00:28:07,037
I started baseball again in my 50s.

851
00:28:07,038 --> 00:28:09,368
- I recall you playing baseball.
- Me too.

852
00:28:09,498 --> 00:28:11,068
Near the end of my 50s,

853
00:28:11,908 --> 00:28:13,938
it was winter.

854
00:28:14,108 --> 00:28:15,877
The ball hit by the opponent...

855
00:28:15,878 --> 00:28:17,677
struck me in my face,

856
00:28:17,678 --> 00:28:19,208
causing an orbital wall fracture.

857
00:28:20,178 --> 00:28:21,178
- That was so dangerous.
- So...

858
00:28:21,179 --> 00:28:22,348
Near the eye?

859
00:28:22,448 --> 00:28:25,088
This scar right here is from back then.

860
00:28:25,448 --> 00:28:27,357
It almost ended my acting career.

861
00:28:27,358 --> 00:28:29,487
But right then, my second son...

862
00:28:29,488 --> 00:28:32,727
had a shotgun wedding and had a daughter.

863
00:28:32,728 --> 00:28:33,957
(A granddaughter from his second son)

864
00:28:33,958 --> 00:28:36,157
My first son's wedding date was already set.

865
00:28:36,158 --> 00:28:39,598
So I told my second son and his wife to live with us for a year...

866
00:28:39,668 --> 00:28:41,938
and hold a wedding on their daughter's first birthday.

867
00:28:42,038 --> 00:28:44,508
While staying at home for six months,

868
00:28:45,138 --> 00:28:47,337
I took care of their daughter.

869
00:28:47,338 --> 00:28:50,348
The joy and laughter from her helped me recover fast.

870
00:28:51,048 --> 00:28:52,277
- That's a relief.
- You are healed by her.

871
00:28:52,278 --> 00:28:54,917
The aftereffects might have lasted 1 or 2 years,

872
00:28:54,918 --> 00:28:56,277
- It lifted your spirits.
- but I returned...

873
00:28:56,278 --> 00:28:57,817
to filming a drama in six months.

874
00:28:57,818 --> 00:28:59,617
- She was a blessing.
- Right.

875
00:28:59,618 --> 00:29:01,087
People ask this question a lot.

876
00:29:01,088 --> 00:29:03,457
"Who do you love more, your son or your grandchildren?"

877
00:29:03,458 --> 00:29:05,427
-You can't compare them.
- People say you can't compare them.

878
00:29:05,428 --> 00:29:06,428
- Of course.
- You can't compare them.

879
00:29:06,429 --> 00:29:07,897
Do you find your grandchild more adorable?

880
00:29:07,898 --> 00:29:09,927
The only reason my sons are even lovable...

881
00:29:09,928 --> 00:29:11,968
is because they gave me grandchildren.

882
00:29:13,498 --> 00:29:15,567
That's true.

883
00:29:15,568 --> 00:29:17,237
That's true.

884
00:29:17,238 --> 00:29:18,607
That's totally right.

885
00:29:18,608 --> 00:29:20,577
You can't compare them.

886
00:29:20,578 --> 00:29:21,578
(His love for his grandchildren is intense.)

887
00:29:21,708 --> 00:29:23,477
My grandmother...

888
00:29:23,478 --> 00:29:25,177
also loved me more than she loved my dad.

889
00:29:25,178 --> 00:29:27,147
- That's right.
- My grandmother.

890
00:29:27,148 --> 00:29:28,647
- She didn't love your dad as much.
- Yes.

891
00:29:28,648 --> 00:29:30,618
She always gave me all the good food.

892
00:29:31,448 --> 00:29:33,118
She didn't mind giving Dad cold food,

893
00:29:33,388 --> 00:29:34,858
- but she always gave me warm food.
- Warm food.

894
00:29:35,318 --> 00:29:36,487
Right.

895
00:29:36,488 --> 00:29:38,887
You ate well even in your childhood.

896
00:29:38,888 --> 00:29:40,897
- I enjoyed all the food.
- That's why she's healthy.

897
00:29:40,898 --> 00:29:42,127
I enjoyed the food.

898
00:29:42,128 --> 00:29:43,157
- You didn't leave any food.
- Of course.

899
00:29:43,158 --> 00:29:44,467
"How well you eat."

900
00:29:44,468 --> 00:29:45,968
"How well you eat."

901
00:29:46,198 --> 00:29:47,867
"That's right."

902
00:29:47,868 --> 00:29:49,967
I always ate three bowls of rice because of that.

903
00:29:49,968 --> 00:29:51,137
Goodness.

904
00:29:51,138 --> 00:29:53,207
She gaslighted me with rice.

905
00:29:53,208 --> 00:29:55,207
- Right.
- Next...

906
00:29:55,208 --> 00:29:56,607
Lastly, for Ha Sun,

907
00:29:56,608 --> 00:29:58,278
- this is really a serious incident.
- Why?

908
00:29:58,548 --> 00:29:59,877
- She wrote "bullying."
- What?

909
00:29:59,878 --> 00:30:01,077
- Ha Seon?
- No.

910
00:30:01,078 --> 00:30:02,078
- That's not good.
- Bullying?

911
00:30:02,079 --> 00:30:03,587
- What do you mean?
- It should not have happened.

912
00:30:03,588 --> 00:30:05,247
Did you bully someone?

913
00:30:05,248 --> 00:30:07,317
- Ha Seon wouldn't do that.
- No wonder.

914
00:30:07,318 --> 00:30:08,957
- I noticed she was wild.
- Right.

915
00:30:08,958 --> 00:30:10,557
- That's right.
- If you were the bully,

916
00:30:10,558 --> 00:30:11,558
we have to film this again...

917
00:30:11,558 --> 00:30:12,558
- from the start.
- Right.

918
00:30:12,559 --> 00:30:13,597
Tell us quickly.

919
00:30:13,598 --> 00:30:14,858
- Tell us.
- So...

920
00:30:15,298 --> 00:30:17,367
- When I was in 12th grade, - Yes.

921
00:30:17,368 --> 00:30:19,927
the golden bell show came to our school.

922
00:30:19,928 --> 00:30:21,267
"The Golden Bell Challenge."

923
00:30:21,268 --> 00:30:22,867
- "The Golden Bell Challenge."
- "The Golden Bell Challenge."

924
00:30:22,868 --> 00:30:25,037
I guess I looked pretty then.

925
00:30:25,038 --> 00:30:27,437
So the writers...

926
00:30:27,438 --> 00:30:29,837
Announcer Kim Bo Min came that day.

927
00:30:29,838 --> 00:30:30,847
The writers told me to act pretty with her.

928
00:30:30,848 --> 00:30:32,207
They told us to act pretty.

929
00:30:32,208 --> 00:30:33,917
So I did that.

930
00:30:33,918 --> 00:30:37,487
After that, the backlash was so big that students were caught...

931
00:30:37,488 --> 00:30:38,618
swearing on camera.

932
00:30:39,148 --> 00:30:40,718
- Because you acted pretty?
- Yes.

933
00:30:40,818 --> 00:30:42,117
- So...
- You were bullied because of that?

934
00:30:42,118 --> 00:30:43,327
Yes. My school was an all-girls school,

935
00:30:43,328 --> 00:30:45,327
so there were a lot of scary girls too.

936
00:30:45,328 --> 00:30:46,797
So, when I took the bus,

937
00:30:46,798 --> 00:30:48,157
they'd swear at me for taking the bus,

938
00:30:48,158 --> 00:30:49,457
and when I walked, they'd open the bus windows...

939
00:30:49,458 --> 00:30:51,027
and yell insults at me.

940
00:30:51,028 --> 00:30:53,097
- I was so scared.
- How did you act pretty that day?

941
00:30:53,098 --> 00:30:54,367
Show us what you did.

942
00:30:54,368 --> 00:30:55,437
- Let's see.
- Let's see.

943
00:30:55,438 --> 00:30:58,267
I just acted pretty and did what they told me to do.

944
00:30:58,268 --> 00:30:59,637
I guess I came off as annoying...

945
00:30:59,638 --> 00:31:00,677
because they thought I voluntarily did that.

946
00:31:00,678 --> 00:31:01,837
But I didn't do it voluntarily.

947
00:31:01,838 --> 00:31:03,277
- I was just told to do it.
- Yes. They told you to do it.

948
00:31:03,278 --> 00:31:05,447
So I just took the taxi even though I didn't have money.

949
00:31:05,448 --> 00:31:06,947
But then I got hate for taking the taxi.

950
00:31:06,948 --> 00:31:07,948
That's right.

951
00:31:07,949 --> 00:31:09,417
- "She's taking the taxi."
- I kept getting hate...

952
00:31:09,418 --> 00:31:11,487
- for a whole year.
- "She thinks she's the princess."

953
00:31:11,488 --> 00:31:13,017
You suffered all that,

954
00:31:13,018 --> 00:31:14,117
and then you even got stalked too?

955
00:31:14,118 --> 00:31:15,217
- What?
- The stalking.

956
00:31:15,218 --> 00:31:18,087
A fan came up to me in my twenties.

957
00:31:18,088 --> 00:31:20,797
You know when fans come to get your autographs,

958
00:31:20,798 --> 00:31:22,097
they ask you to write, "I love you."

959
00:31:22,098 --> 00:31:23,327
- That's right.
- "Please write, 'I love you.'"

960
00:31:23,328 --> 00:31:25,267
- "Please write, 'I love you.'"
- I normally don't write that,

961
00:31:25,268 --> 00:31:26,627
but the fan said, "Just write it for me."

962
00:31:26,628 --> 00:31:27,967
He got angry, so I just wrote it for him.

963
00:31:27,968 --> 00:31:29,797
But that was the first day of our relationship for him.

964
00:31:29,798 --> 00:31:31,407
- That's what he thought.
- Since then...

965
00:31:31,408 --> 00:31:32,937
- He came near my place.
- "You said..."

